[1] Maryland - groundhog, human exposure
Date: Tue 9 Aug 2016
Source: SoMdNews [edited]
http://www.somdnews.com/breaking/groundhog-that-bit-person-in-leonardtown-tests-positive-for-rabies/article_3e2ab836-de5d-5939-808f-9eb589dcdb02.html


A groundhog [also known as a woodchuck, _Marmota monax_] that bit a human in Leonardtown [Maryland] tested positive for rabies, the St. Mary's County Health Department reported Tuesday afternoon [9 Aug 2016].

The incident occurred the evening of Saturday, 30 Jul 2016, at Fairwood Court in Leonardtown, off Route 5 south of the St. Mary's County Fairgrounds.

The groundhog is the 11th animal from St. Mary's County this year [2016] confirmed through laboratory testing to have rabies. Six raccoons, 3 skunks and 1 cat have been confirmed as rabid since 1 Jan 2016, according to the health department. Five animals from St. Mary's County were confirmed in 2015 to have rabies -- 3 raccoons and 2 cats.

Rabies is a potentially fatal virus that is transmitted through the saliva of an infected animal. Exposure may occur through a bite, scratch or contact with saliva to broken skin or mucous membranes such as the eyes or nose. All animal bites or exposures should be reported promptly to allow for appropriate rabies prevention measures.

The St. Mary's County Health Department in a press release urged residents to practice rabies protection this summer and throughout the year by vaccinating their pets and avoiding contact with wild animals that display unusual or aggressive behavior.

Vaccination of pets is a 1st line of defense against rabies. Pet owners are encouraged to review the shot records of their pets with a veterinarian. The St. Mary's Animal Welfare League holds monthly rabies vaccine clinics March through November for a cost of USD 15 per vaccine. Clinic dates for the remainder of 2016 are 12 Sep, 10 Oct and 14 Nov from 6 to 8 p.m. at the county fairgrounds in Leonardtown.

To report a bite by any animal, contact the St. Mary's County Sheriff's Office at 301-475-8008. For more information about rabies and the rabies vaccination clinics, visit the health department's website at http://www.smchd.org.

[Byline: Jesse Yeatman]

