[2] Pennsylvania - coyote, human exposure
Date: Tue 9 Aug 2016
Source: Pittsburgh Post Gazette [edited]
http://www.post-gazette.com/local/south/2016/08/09/Coyote-tests-positive-for-rabies-after-attacking-Lincoln-man/stories/201608090198


A coyote that tested positive for rabies was shot and killed hours after it attacked and bit a man on Monday night [8 Aug 2016] in Lincoln Borough [Pennsylvania], according to the Allegheny County Health Department.

The coyote was shot Tuesday [9 Aug 2016] by officers with the Lincoln Police Department, the county said, and Pennsylvania Game Commission employees took its carcass to the health department lab, where it tested positive for rabies.

The bite victim, who was identified only as an adult male, has already begun post-exposure treatment, the health department said. Even though the rabid coyote was killed, the health department warned that because coyotes are pack animals, others may be infected.

The health department advises anyone who is bitten, scratched or exposed to saliva from a stray or any other unknown animal to immediately cleanse the contact area with soap and water, seek emergency medical treatment, and report the incident to the health department.

The Allegheny County Health Department can be reached at 412-687-2243. The health department also says to use caution when pets are left outside. Residents should get their pets a rabies vaccine and keep them away from stray or wild animals. Wear rubber gloves to handle any pet that comes into contact with a stray animal, cleanse any wounds, and bring it to a veterinarian for an examination.

The rabies virus can be transmitted through a bite or scratch and is usually fatal if left untreated. But the vaccination is highly effective when given quickly after a rabies exposure [post-exposure prophylaxis - Mod.TG].

[Byline: Andrew Goldstein]

