[3] Texas - bat, human exposure
Date: Fri 12 Aug 2016
Source: Seguin Gazette [edited]
http://seguingazette.com/news/article_09e5ded2-5fc7-11e6-9477-7fa02d97e0b6.html


A Seguin [Texas] man was bit by a rabid bat after his dog alerted him to the creature's presence in the home on Sunday [7 Aug 2016].

Seguin Police Deputy Chief Bruce Ure said the man reported the incident happened on Sunday in the 1600 block of Eastwood Drive.

"The gentleman's dog alerted him to the bat by barking, it was actually inside his house," he said.

Believing the bat was dead, the man tried to pick it up to remove it, Ure said.

"When he went down to pick it up and throw it away, that's when the bat bit him on the left thumb," he said.

The man went to Guadalupe Regional Medical Center for treatment.

While Nicole Patek, GRMC executive director of emergency services, can't comment on specific cases, she said it is typical for the hospital to give victims an immunization shot, as well as start the rabies series.

"Depending on the animal, we treat the bites the same way," she said. "We administer the same treatment because we don't wait for the information to determine if the animal is rabid. We administer the immune globulin for the rabies. It is a vaccination and the 1st day they are here, they get an injection into the site of the bite."

The series includes 4, sometimes 5 additional shots over a 14 to 28 day period, Patek said. [It should be noted these shots are given in the muscle, usually the arm muscle. - Mod.TG]

"We have day zero, and bring them back at days 3, 7, and 14 and sometimes 28," she said.

Determining who can avoid going through the series of shots depends on the animal and whether there is proof of rabies vaccination, Patek said.

"If they haven't had their rabies shots or we can't prove that they have or can't capture the animal, we usually err on the side of caution," she said. "If it's your dog, kept inside and you vaccinate your animals, we probably don't need to start the treatment. If it is any kind of risky animal or you can't verify if they are vaccinated then we have to start the treatment."

Following the report, the offending bat was sent to the State Health Services lab for rabies testing and came back positive, Ure said.

"That is the case 100 percent of the time," he said. "Other circumstances will determine whether we send the bat or any animal off to testing. There are other extenuating circumstances that we would look at before we submit it for testing at the state."

According to the Center for Disease Control website, rabies is transmitted by coming in contact with the saliva or brain/nervous system tissue of an infected mammal.

"You can only get rabies by coming in contact with these specific bodily excretions and tissues," the site said. "The most common mode of rabies virus transmission is through the bite and virus-containing saliva of an infected host."

It is unknown if the Chihuahua, who let his homeowner know about the unwanted intruder, was bitten, but nonetheless the pup has to be quarantined as a precaution to make sure the disease wasn't transmitted, Ure said.

"Really the dog is the hero in this whole deal because he is the one who alerted his owner to the bat," he said. "This little guy alerted his homeowner to a rabid bat, and now he's getting stuck in a crate for 45 days with no contact from anyone."

Ure said the police department and Seguin Animal Services are allowing the dogs owners to participate in an at-home quarantine.

"We are coordinating a home quarantine with the dog's owner," he said. "Even though the dog was up-to-date on his rabies vaccine, state law says in a scenario like this, we have to quarantine the animal, and we believe home quarantine is appropriate."

In order to avoid being a potential victim, Ure recommends leaving the bat handling to the professionals.

"We recommend, if you [or] someone were to find a sick or deceased bat to notify our animal services and we'll come out and investigate," he said. "A bat laying on the ground is 10 times more dangerous than a bat flying in the air. Rule number one is never handle a bat, even to attempt to try to pick up what appears to be a deceased bat, even with a shovel, because the bat might be agitated and come after you if it is sick and aggressive."

With large bat colonies nearby like the Bracken Bat Cave -- believed to be the largest colony of Mexican free-tailed bats in the world -- just northeast of San Antonio and the South Congress Bridge in Austin, it's not uncommon to see bats in the area.

"Bats in general are great for the environment and we like bats, but they are known to be carriers of rabies," Ure said.

Additionally, reports of bat bites are not common, Ure said.

"It is very rare," he said. "When it does happen, it is an extremely serious event. In this instance, the bat was inside the house. It is not uncommon for bats to come into a house if the door is open, especially a sick bat."

Patek added that anybody bitten should seek medical attention immediately to reduce any chance of infection.

"We encourage people to come in right away when they are bit," she said. "We take a report based on the animal information and we have to report that to animal control, whether it be the county or the city where it occurred. The physician or nurse practitioner will see them from there and provide guidance on what course of action would be necessary."

To report a sick, injured or dead animal call Seguin Animal Services at 830-379-2123 or Guadalupe County Animal Control 830-379-1224.

[Byline: Felicia Frazar]

